# The Chemistry of Belonging: On Empathy, Civic Virtue, and the Architecture of Who We See

---

The ideal form of democracy, on which our American republic is founded, is often considered to be a form of republicanism — a foundational political ideology centered on citizenship, the common good, and popular sovereignty. Republicanism requires that the ultimate political authority resides within the people who delegate this power to elected representatives. It demands civic virtue — that all citizens actively participate in public life and subordinate their private interests for the sake of the community in order to function. In it, government is strictly limited by a constitution preventing the arbitrary exercise of power and it emphasizes that true freedom means no individual or group has the structural power to dominate another.

Sounds great, doesn't it? So why hasn't it worked like we planned?

Because despite our best efforts, individual knowledge within U.S. society has declined over time, and knowledge of economics, history, law, and politics is something civic virtue needs in order to operate. It requires citizens to care about their country and to be educated enough to understand how to guide policy and organize to enforce, define, and maintain their rights. The decline in individual knowledge was not an abstract worry for the founders of the American republic. It was a preoccupation that showed up in their letters, their legislation, and their institutional design.

The clearest version comes from Jefferson, who returned to this theme repeatedly. His most cited line is from a letter to Colonel Charles Yancey, written on January 6, 1816: "If a nation expects to be ignorant and free, in a state of civilization, it expects what never was and never will be." He pushed relentlessly for public education in Virginia — his Bill for the More General Diffusion of Knowledge, drafted in 1779, was built on the premise that self-governance required an informed citizenry. That the Bill failed in the Virginia legislature — presented in 1778 and again in 1780, championed by Madison while Jefferson served abroad, and finally passed only in a gutted, toothless version in 1796 — is itself instructive. The anxiety was there. The political will was not. Even among the founders, the society they were building resisted the very investment in public education they argued was necessary for its survival.

Madison carried a version of the same worry. His often-quoted line from an 1822 letter to W.T. Barry: "A popular Government, without popular information, or the means of acquiring it, is but a Prologue to a Farce or a Tragedy; or, perhaps both." Adams was blunter and more pessimistic. He worried less about education specifically and more about whether the passions of the public could be contained by any institutional structure — his *Defence of the Constitutions* is essentially a long argument that democracy without structural checks will consume itself.

The concern they expressed wasn't just about literacy or knowledge of civics. It was about the capacity for judgment — the ability to weigh, to deliberate, and to resist manipulation. Jefferson's "ignorance" isn't merely the absence of information. It is the absence of the wondering, doubting disposition that makes self-governance possible rather than performative. The Electoral College, the original appointment of senators by state legislatures, property requirements for voting — all of these were partly structural responses to exactly that anxiety. Whether you read them as prudent safeguards or as elite gatekeeping depends on your angle, but the underlying worry was real and persistent: that the experiment fails if the people lack the capacity to sustain it.

And what does that capacity look like today? The Annenberg Public Policy Center's 2023 Constitution Day Civics Survey found that one in six American adults cannot name any of the three branches of government, and only one in twenty can name all five freedoms protected by the First Amendment. A 1998 national survey commissioned by the Minneapolis Federal Reserve found that adults scored an average of forty-five percent on questions testing basic economic concepts — a result the researchers characterized as functional economic illiteracy. The National Assessment of Educational Progress has tested economics only twice, in 2006 and 2012, and has not administered the assessment since; the last time it did, fifty-seven percent of twelfth graders demonstrated only "basic" or "below basic" understanding of economic fundamentals — a subject the nation apparently considers too peripheral to measure regularly. Meanwhile, NAEP civics scores for eighth graders declined in 2022 for the first time since the assessment began, with about a third of students unable to meet even the basic benchmark — meaning they likely cannot describe the structure and function of their own government. The 2024 NAEP results for twelfth graders showed continued declines in both reading and mathematics, with scores at the lowest levels in more than a decade.

Something shifted, and it wasn't just the quantity of education but its character. Pre-World War II American education treated political economy as inseparable from civics. You couldn't understand self-governance without understanding how economies work, who benefits from what arrangements, and what trade-offs mean. That integration was baked into the progressive-era curriculum. After the war, economics as a discipline underwent a transformation — it professionalized, mathematicized, and increasingly defined itself as a technical science rather than a branch of moral and political reasoning. Samuelson's *Foundations of Economic Analysis* (1947) is often cited as a symbolic inflection point, but the shift was broader and more institutional than any single book: graduate programs reoriented around econometrics, the discipline severed its roots in political philosophy, and what filtered into high school curricula reflected the narrowing. Economics became a specialist subject rather than general literacy. The average student of the 1930s and 1940s was educated within a framework where economic reasoning was treated as a civic capacity. The modern student encounters economics, if at all, as a technical discipline disconnected from self-governance. The literacy didn't just decline — the category shifted. What counted as knowing economics changed in a way that made the civic dimension invisible. The capacity Jefferson was worried about wasn't mastery of supply-and-demand curves. It was the ability to understand who gains and who loses from any given arrangement — and that is exactly what has been systematically removed.

Beyond knowledge, sustaining the republic meant the capacity to care, and to believe that citizens and their votes could play a meaningful role in shaping their city, state, and nation's future. But the most common thing you hear now is that people feel helpless to really affect change. They understand, broadly, that things are wrong. They are often unsure what to do about it, or they feel a deep apathy toward politics in general — a sense that the system doesn't respond to them and never will regardless of what they do.

Why did we stop educating ourselves? Why did we stop caring? And what, if anything, does biology have to do with it?

---

To begin to answer that, it helps to step back and look at when and why Americans *did* care — and what made them stop. When Alexis de Tocqueville visited the United States in the 1830s, what struck him most was not the government but the civic associations — Americans "of all ages, all stations in life, and all types of disposition," forever forming groups, joining clubs, organizing themselves into collective action. This propensity for association, he believed, was the engine of American democracy. Not the Constitution. Not the presidency. The fact that ordinary people practiced being citizens together, in rooms, over time.

Robert Putnam, in *Bowling Alone* (2000), measured what happened when that practice stopped. Beginning in the 1960s and accelerating through the 1980s and 1990s, participation in virtually every form of civic life declined — voting, church attendance, union membership, PTA involvement, lodge membership, dinner parties with neighbors. He estimated the causes: fifty percent generational change (the civic generation aging out), twenty-five percent television, ten percent work and commuting pressures, ten percent suburbanization. Theda Skocpol, in *Diminished Democracy* (2003), traced the organizational dimension of the same decline — how the voluntary federations that once brought citizens together across class lines hollowed into professionalized lobbying firms that spoke *for* people rather than gathering them in rooms.

But both frameworks, for all their empirical rigor, ask the question from the wrong end. They document *what* declined and *when*. They offer reasonable hypotheses about *why*. What they don't fully address is the prior question: what produced all that civic engagement in the first place? Why were those earlier generations so remarkably organized? The standard answer is that they were better people — more civic-minded, more community-oriented, more willing to sacrifice for the common good. This is the nostalgia reading, and it is almost certainly wrong. The historical record tells a different story, and it begins not in political science but in labor history.

The extraordinary civic engagement of the mid-twentieth century wasn't produced by moral superiority. It was produced by a convergence of conditions that made self-organization — and the self-education it required — a matter of survival.

Consider the workers' education movement of the 1920s and 1930s. In that period, the Workers' Education Bureau of America provided guidance and funding to some seventy labor colleges around the country. Workers' Circles offered language acquisition and literature appreciation. The curriculum wasn't limited to vocational training — it included political economy, labor history, rhetoric, parliamentary procedure. Workers were educating themselves, not because they had a philosophical commitment to lifelong learning, but because they needed to understand why their wages were what they were, how unions functioned, and what rights they could claim. The education was a tool. A tool for not getting crushed.

The Flint sit-down strike of 1936 offers one of history's most vivid illustrations. A day into their occupation of a General Motors plant, the autoworkers set up a school. Surrounded by idle machines, freed from the foreman's oversight, they took classes in public speaking, labor journalism, political economy, and the history of the labor movement. Nobody credentialed those workers. Nobody assigned them a reading list. They educated themselves because the stakes required it.

And then there were the Armed Services Editions — perhaps the most extraordinary mass literacy event in American history. From 1943 to 1947, over 122 million copies of more than 1,300 titles were distributed free to military personnel. These small, pocket-sized paperbacks were designed to fit in a soldier's cargo pants, and they were, according to contemporary accounts, as popular as pin-up illustrations. Soldiers tore them into sections so multiple people could read simultaneously. General Eisenhower requested that a special set be reserved so that each service member received a book as they boarded the D-Day landing craft.

The critical detail, recorded by Molly Guptill Manning in *When Books Went to War*: the Armed Services Editions were the first books some readers had picked up since high school. For some, they were the first books they had ever read cover to cover. Publishers were delighted to learn that many letter-writers had not been readers at home but were now, as they put it, "hooked on books."

Why? Because there was nothing else to do. When you strip away entertainment options — when there is no television, no radio half the time, no diversions beyond cards and conversation — books become the default medium. The soldiers weren't educating themselves because someone told them to. They were doing it because the conditions — boredom, fear, the need to understand what they were fighting for — made reading the most available and most useful thing they could do.

The post-war effect was measurable. Paperback sales skyrocketed from 40 million in 1943 to 95 million in 1947. By 1959, paperback sales exceeded hardcover for the first time — driven partly by the reading habits the war had created, partly by innovations in mass-market distribution, and partly by the growth of genre fiction. And then came television. In 1950, only nine percent of American households owned a set. By decade's end, that number was eighty-seven percent. Dutch longitudinal research on reading habits found that the strongest decline in time spent reading, especially books, occurred during the initial phase of television adoption (1955–1975), with competition from television identified as the most evident cause. A 1955 Gallup poll found that only thirty-nine percent of Americans had read even one book that year — despite having the highest level of formal education in the English-speaking world. The medium that had filled soldiers' idle hours was being replaced by one that required nothing from its audience except passive attention.

The pattern is not mysterious. People educate themselves when conditions demand it. They stop when conditions change. Education is not a natural human pastime. It is a tool — perhaps the most powerful one our species has produced — but a tool nonetheless. And like all tools, it gets picked up when the job requires it and set down when the job is done.

---

This observation about education becomes even sharper when placed against the economic data.

The period from roughly 1940 to 1970 — what economists Claudia Goldin and Robert Margo termed "The Great Compression" — represents something close to the ideal conditions for civic engagement among those who were permitted to participate. That qualification matters, and it must be stated directly: the mid-century civic architecture that Putnam and Tocqueville celebrated was built on exclusion. Many of those bowling leagues were segregated. Many of those unions barred Black workers or confined them to separate locals. The lodges, the fraternal orders, the women's clubs — much of this infrastructure achieved its high internal cohesion by enforcing rigid, homogeneous boundaries. Jim Crow was not incidental to the mid-century civic landscape. It was structural to it. McCarthyism chilled political dissent. Redlining confined Black families to neighborhoods systematically stripped of resources. Any honest account of this period must hold two things at once: the civic engagement was real, and it was built on a foundation of profound exclusion.

Within those boundaries, for those who were included, conditions aligned. Income inequality shrank dramatically. Wage controls during the war prevented growth at the top. Progressive taxation, Social Security, and the power of unions kept low- and middle-income growth strong afterward. The Gini coefficient was flat or declining for a generation.

During this same period, education expanded massively. The GI Bill sent millions of veterans to college. The number of bachelor's degrees awarded doubled between 1940 and 1950. Suzanne Mettler's *Soldiers to Citizens* (2005) found that GI Bill usage promoted approximately fifty percent more civic organization memberships and roughly thirty percent more political activities among veterans compared to non-users, controlling for other factors. But even here, the exclusion was present: NBER research has shown that for Black veterans confined to educational choices in the South, the GI Bill exacerbated rather than narrowed the economic and educational gap between Black and white Americans.

Goldin and Katz's *The Race Between Education and Technology* (2008) showed that during the first eight decades of the twentieth century, the supply of educated workers grew faster than demand, which boosted incomes broadly and lowered inequality. After 1980, that reversed. The college wage premium climbed back to its 1915 level by 2005. And the civic infrastructure that Putnam mourned didn't just happen to decline during this period. It declined because the conditions that produced it — shared economic struggle, limited entertainment alternatives, a labor movement that required self-education and organization, a relatively compressed income distribution that kept people in proximity to each other's problems — were systematically dismantled. Not through conspiracy. Through the accumulated logic of convenience, prosperity, and technological change.

Skocpol's *Diminished Democracy* provides the organizational autopsy of what this dismantling actually looked like on the ground. Her research documents a transformation that began in the 1960s: the nation's civic life shifted from membership to management. The voluntary federations that had brought citizens together across class lines — the lodges, the fraternal orders, the unions, the women's clubs — were replaced by professionally managed advocacy organizations. The new organizations spoke *for* people rather than requiring people to speak for themselves. They were more efficient, more targeted, more effective at lobbying. They were also, in Skocpol's devastating phrase, "remarkably oligarchic." More voices were not the same thing as increased democratic capacity.

The civic muscle, in other words, atrophied not because people became lazy, but because the institutional structure no longer required its exercise. The protections that unions had fought for became codified in law — OSHA, the NLRA, workplace safety regulations. Worker fatality rates dropped from 18 per 100,000 in 1970 to 3.3 by 2013. The organizing that had been necessary to win those protections became, in a perverse sense, unnecessary once the protections existed.

Putnam asked: why did people stop bowling in leagues? The deeper question is: why did they start? And the answer, when you trace it back far enough, is that they had to. The bowling league, the lodge, the union hall, the PTA meeting — these were not expressions of civic idealism. They were infrastructures of mutual survival. People practiced democracy together because the alternative was being alone in a system that didn't care about them individually. When institutional protections made that aloneness survivable, the practice stopped. Not because the virtue died. Because the necessity did.

---

So far, this is a story about institutions, economics, and historical conditions — the kind of narrative political scientists and sociologists are equipped to tell. But underneath all of it, underneath the policy decisions and the cultural shifts and the technological transformations, there is something older and more fundamental. There is biology. And the biology, while it does not explain everything, illuminates a dimension of civic engagement that purely institutional accounts consistently miss.

Frans de Waal, the Dutch-American primatologist who spent decades studying empathy and cooperation at Emory University before his death in March 2024, established something that would have been heresy to Thomas Hobbes: cooperation, at least within the group, is the default. "Humans and other primates are by default cooperators within their own ingroup," de Waal told researchers at Google's Empathy Lab, "and there are brain studies now that indicate that the first choice is a cooperative choice. Secondarily, we start to think about the selfish choices."

This is the inverse of the Hobbesian premise that undergirds most of Western political philosophy. Hobbes looked at the English Civil War — a specific political catastrophe in a specific country at a specific moment — and universalized it into a theory of all humanity. Without a sovereign to restrain them, he argued, humans would descend into a war of all against all. Life without government would be "solitary, poor, nasty, brutish, and short."

De Waal's primates told a different story. Chimpanzees reconcile after conflicts. They console distressed companions by putting an arm around them. They share food, cooperate in hunting, and punish free-riders. Bonobos resolve conflicts through affection rather than aggression. The evolutionary logic is straightforward: a social species whose members depend on each other for survival needs a mechanism to maintain social bonds. Empathy — the involuntary experience of another's distress as one's own — is that mechanism. It didn't evolve because it's noble. It evolved because it works.

But here is the critical qualification, and it changes everything about how we understand civic engagement, group formation, and the invisible architecture of who we choose to see. De Waal's crucial phrase is "within their own ingroup." Not across groups. *Within*.

The neuroscience of this specificity is now well-documented, and its mechanism has a name: parochial altruism. The term describes a behavioral pattern observed across species and confirmed in controlled human experiments — self-sacrifice to benefit the ingroup, combined with indifference toward competing outgroups. And the biochemistry that drives it is oxytocin, the same neuropeptide popularly known as the "love hormone" or the "bonding chemical."

Carsten De Dreu's groundbreaking research, published in *Science* in 2010, established what many would prefer not to know: oxytocin-motivated cooperation is mostly parochial. It motivates ingroup favoritism, cooperation toward ingroup but not outgroup members, and defense-motivated non-cooperation toward threatening outsiders. In double-blind, placebo-controlled experiments, intranasal administration of oxytocin enhanced ingroup favoritism in social trust, empathy for pain, and cooperation. Critically, the finding is specific: De Dreu's data showed that oxytocin did not increase active hostility toward outgroups. What it did was fail to extend the cooperative impulse beyond the boundary of the group. The distinction matters. The primary danger of parochial empathy is not that it makes us hate those outside our group. It is that it makes us indifferent to them — neurochemically incapable of registering their suffering with the same weight we give to our own people's.

The same chemical that makes you care about your group makes others invisible to you.

The neurological findings deepen the picture. Research published in *Neuron* found that failure to help outgroup members was predicted by activation of the nucleus accumbens — the brain's reward center — suggesting that in some cases, the brain processes outgroup disadvantage with something uncomfortably close to satisfaction. EEG research from Oxford demonstrated that people generally do not vicariously feel the emotional and motivational states of those they categorize as outgroup members. The more prejudiced the person, the less likely they were to intuitively catch the emotive states of people outside their group.

Perhaps most disturbing of all: the mere assignment of participants into arbitrary social groups — teams created in a lab, with no prior history, no shared culture, no real stakes — was sufficient to produce empathic bias. People showed more empathy for the pain of people wearing their team color and less for those wearing another. Some showed counter-empathic responses — measurable satisfaction at an outgroup member's adversity. Schadenfreude, it turns out, is not a character flaw. It is a neurological event triggered by the simplest possible social categorization.

And much of this happens below conscious awareness. De Dreu's comprehensive review found that both categorization of self and others into in- and outgroups and discriminatory preferences for the ingroup are fast, automatic, and modulated by subcortical brain structures disconnected from executive control and cognitive monitoring. The sorting happens before your conscious mind has a chance to intervene. You don't decide who to empathize with. The biochemistry sets a powerful, subcortical baseline that your conscious mind then struggles to override — and usually justifies after the fact.

---

The neuroscience described above comes primarily from controlled laboratory experiments — small groups, intranasal oxytocin, carefully measured responses. Extrapolating from these studies to large-scale social phenomena like mob violence or political polarization requires caution. Nobody has measured neuropeptide cascades in a rioter's bloodstream mid-mob. What the lab research establishes is a mechanism — a powerful, subcortical tendency toward ingroup bonding and outgroup indifference — and a reasonable inference that this mechanism operates in parallel with the social and psychological dynamics of group behavior. It does not establish that oxytocin *causes* mob violence in any simple, direct sense.

With that caveat, the mechanism does make mob violence more legible. In conditions of intense group cohesion — a rally, a protest that turns violent, a crowd swept into collective action — the dynamics the laboratory research identifies would be operating at heightened intensity. Group identity intensifies. The empathic boundary contracts. The people around you become hyper-ingroup — your concern for them spikes. And simultaneously, the capacity to register the suffering of anyone outside that boundary diminishes. Not because anyone chooses indifference. Because the conditions suppress the deliberative capacity — the prefrontal cortex, the part of the brain that says *wait, think, consider consequences* — that would normally check the behavior.

This is consistent with what we know about individuals in mobs doing things they would never do alone. Not because they become different people, but because the conditions of intense group bonding suppress the deliberative capacity that would normally check the behavior. The empathic mechanism is functioning — it has simply been narrowed so tightly that it applies only to those immediately beside you. Everyone else falls outside its reach.

---

If empathy is bounded — if the neurochemistry that makes us care about some people simultaneously renders others invisible — then the question that matters most is whether the boundary can be moved. Whether someone who is *them* can become *us*.

The story of Ann Atwater and C.P. Ellis suggests that it can. But how that happens is not what most people assume, and understanding this distinction may be the most important thing the neuroscience has to offer the political conversation.

In 1971, Durham, North Carolina was a city ripped open by the court-ordered desegregation of its public schools. Ann Atwater was a civil rights activist, fierce and uncompromising, known for physically turning city councilmen's chairs back to face her when they swiveled away to avoid listening. C.P. Ellis was the Exalted Cyclops of the Durham chapter of the Ku Klux Klan — a man so consumed by racial hatred that Atwater once had to be restrained from attacking him with a knife at a public meeting. Ellis later admitted he thought Atwater was "the meanest black woman I'd ever seen in my life." She regarded him as everything she was fighting against.

They were selected to co-chair a charrette — a series of intensive, multi-day community meetings designed to address the desegregation crisis. Neither wanted the assignment. Both accepted because refusing would have meant ceding control to the other.

What happened over the course of those meetings was not an intellectual conversion. Nobody presented Ellis with a persuasive argument against racism or showed him data on the benefits of integration. Sitting across from Atwater day after day, working on the same problem, Ellis began to recognize something that had been invisible to him for his entire adult life. Her struggles — with poverty, with being dismissed by powerful people, with trying to secure a decent education for her children in a system that didn't care about them — mirrored his own. "Mr. Ellis has the same problems with the schools and his children as I do with mine," Atwater observed later.

There is a small detail from the charrette that says more than any research paper could. At one session, a gospel choir performed. Atwater noticed that Ellis was awkwardly clapping along to the music, completely off the beat. In a gesture so instinctive it may not have been a conscious decision at all, Atwater reached over and took Ellis's hands in hers, guiding them into the rhythm. A civil rights activist and a Klansman, clapping together. The boundary, in that moment, was being crossed — not through argument, not through education, but through the irreducible physical reality of one human being touching another.

The empathic boundary moved. Not because someone explained why it should. Because the conditions — sustained proximity, a shared problem, mutual vulnerability, the undeniable presence of another human being over time — made reclassification possible. Ellis began to register Atwater as someone whose pain mattered to him. Her suffering became legible. Not because he decided to care. Because something shifted beneath deliberation.

At the final session, Ellis held up his Klan membership card and addressed the room, his voice trembling: "She is trying to help her people just like I'm trying to help my people." Then: "If schools are going to be better by me tearing up this card, I shall do so." He tore it up. He never went back to the Klan. He became a labor organizer, negotiated Durham's first paid holiday for Martin Luther King Jr.'s birthday, and remained friends with Atwater for the rest of his life. She delivered the eulogy at his funeral in 2005. Both of them, after the charrette, went back to school and earned their high school equivalency degrees.

The lesson of Durham is not that education overcomes prejudice. It is not that rational argument defeats bias. The lesson is that the empathic boundary can be crossed by direct encounter — sustained, proximate, real enough that something beneath conscious thought recalibrates.

And Durham is not an isolated case. Gordon Allport first formalized the contact hypothesis in 1954, proposing that intergroup contact under certain conditions — equal status, common goals, cooperation, institutional support — could reduce prejudice. In the same year, Muzafer Sherif's Robbers Cave experiment demonstrated the principle in controlled conditions: eleven-year-old boys divided into rival groups at a summer camp developed intense mutual hostility within days, but when researchers introduced problems that could only be solved through cooperation between the groups — a broken water supply, a stalled truck — the hostility dissolved and cross-group friendships formed. Contact alone didn't do it. Contact combined with shared, cooperative goals did.

In 2006, Thomas Pettigrew and Linda Tropp published a meta-analysis of 515 separate studies, drawing on over 250,000 subjects across 38 countries and spanning six decades of research. Their finding was unambiguous: intergroup contact typically reduces prejudice, and the effect holds across racial, ethnic, and other social group categories. Critically, they also found that Allport's conditions, while they amplified the effect, were not essential — even unstructured contact showed prejudice reduction, though structured contact with shared goals produced substantially stronger results. A 2018 reanalysis limited to the most rigorous experimental designs — random assignment, delayed outcome measures — confirmed the core finding, while noting that effects were weaker for racial and ethnic prejudice specifically, the domain where the work is hardest and most needed.

What this body of research establishes is that the Atwater-Ellis story, extraordinary as it is, exemplifies a mechanism that has been documented hundreds of times across decades. The boundary can be moved. It is moved through encounter — sustained, proximate, structured around shared purpose. No lecture accomplishes this alone. No policy mandate accomplishes this alone. But the mechanism is real, it is replicable, and it operates below conscious thought in ways that the neuroscience and the social psychology converge in confirming.

---

The things that cross empathic boundaries operate at human scale — face to face, person to person. They require time, proximity, and the full sensory presence of another human being. They cannot be industrialized, scaled, or automated.

The things that create and reinforce empathic boundaries can be amplified to millions through technology.

This asymmetry is not incidental. It is structural, and understanding why it exists matters. Crossing an empathic boundary requires the slow, metabolically expensive work of the prefrontal cortex — deliberation, perspective-taking, the conscious override of subcortical defaults. It requires sustained attention to a specific individual whose reality is complex enough to resist easy categorization. It cannot be compressed, sped up, or distributed. It is, by its nature, inefficient.

Reinforcing an empathic boundary requires none of that. It requires only a signal — a group marker, a threat cue, an emotional trigger — that activates the fast, automatic, subcortical sorting system. And signals can be broadcast. A rally does it. A propaganda poster does it. A viral post does it. An algorithm optimized for engagement does it, because engagement metrics reward emotional arousal, and content that activates ingroup solidarity and outgroup suspicion reliably produces arousal. The technology doesn't need to understand the neurochemistry. It only needs to optimize for the behavioral outputs that the neurochemistry produces — clicks, shares, time-on-platform — and the sorting takes care of itself.

The filter bubble, in this light, is not merely an information problem — though it is that. It is also, plausibly, an empathy problem. When you encounter a narrower range of people, you have fewer opportunities for the kind of contact that the research shows can reduce prejudice. You see less suffering outside your group. You encounter fewer stories that challenge your categorizations. Whether this narrows empathic capacity in the neurochemical sense that the laboratory research describes, or simply reduces the social conditions under which empathy can extend, the practical result is similar: the boundary hardens. The group tightens. Indifference toward everyone outside it increases. And this happens continuously, automatically, at speeds and scales no previous technology has achieved.

This asymmetry — between the human-scale process that crosses empathic boundaries and the industrial-scale technologies that reinforce them — forces a reconsideration not just of our current political crises, but of what civic virtue actually was and why it disappeared.

---

Civic virtue, in the republican tradition from Aristotle through the American founders, is the willingness to subordinate private interest to the common good. It is the defining quality of the citizen. It is what makes self-governance possible. And its decline is typically narrated as a moral story — we lost something precious, something that earlier generations possessed and we have squandered.

But the biology and the history, taken together, tell a different story.

Civic virtue was never a natural human excellence. It was a compensatory mechanism — a behavior produced by specific material conditions in societies too large and too complex for the relational knowledge of small-scale groups to maintain order. In a band of 50 people, you don't need civic virtue. You have something older and more organic: relational wisdom — the interpersonal knowledge of who everyone is, what they need, how to maintain balance. Justice is embedded in the web of relationships. You don't need a theory of rights when the social fabric *is* the justice system.

But when societies scale beyond the reach of relational knowledge — when you are governed by people you will never meet, when economic relationships extend beyond reciprocity, when hierarchy introduces structural asymmetries that cannot be resolved through interpersonal negotiation — that is when civic virtue becomes necessary. Not as an ideal, but as a prosthetic. A compensatory technology for lost relational proximity.

The union worker who read political economy wasn't pursuing enlightenment. She was compensating for the fact that she couldn't walk over to the person exploiting her and renegotiate the relationship face to face. The education was a prosthetic for a social connection that industrial capitalism had severed. And when institutional protections replaced the need for that prosthetic — when OSHA and the NLRA and codified labor law did what workers had once had to do for themselves — the prosthetic was set aside. Not because people became morally worse. Because the tool was no longer necessary for survival.

The decline of civic virtue is not the story of a species that lost its way. It is the story of a compensatory behavior that emerged under pressure and receded when the pressure was removed — without anyone noticing that nothing had been built to replace it.

---

Which brings us back to Jefferson, and to the question with which we began.

Jefferson feared ignorance. The neuroscience reveals the limits of empathy. Both were right, and neither is sufficient without the other. This is the synthesis the conversation about civic decline has been missing: education and empathy are not competing explanations for the crisis. They are co-requirements, and both are in collapse, for related but distinct reasons.

You cannot govern yourself if you do not understand how economics works, how law is made, who benefits from which arrangements, and what leverage you have within the system. That is the educational dimension, and the founders were correct that its absence is fatal to self-governance. A citizen who feels deeply for her neighbor but cannot read a budget, cannot follow a policy argument, cannot distinguish between a structural problem and a personal failing — that citizen is not equipped to participate in republican government, no matter how much she cares. Empathy without knowledge is compassion with no direction. It can be moved. It can be manipulated. It can be aimed at whatever target the most emotionally potent message points it toward.

But you also cannot govern yourself if your capacity for concern extends only to people who look, think, and live like you — if the conditions of your life have narrowed your empathic range until everyone outside your immediate circle is invisible. That is the empathic dimension, and it is the one that political theory has largely ignored. A citizen who understands economics perfectly but whose empathic boundary has been narrowed by sorting and isolation — that citizen will use his knowledge to serve his group at the expense of others and call it rational self-interest. Education without empathy is competence in service of tribalism.

The workers' education movement understood this intuitively, even without the neuroscience. The union hall was never just a classroom. It was a room. A room where people who were different from each other — different trades, different backgrounds, sometimes different races and languages — sat together, argued together, organized together. The education happened in the context of encounter. The knowledge was acquired alongside the expansion of the empathic boundary. You learned political economy while sitting next to someone whose experience of exploitation was different from yours but recognizably real. The Flint strikers didn't just study labor history in the abstract. They studied it while depending on each other for food, safety, and solidarity. The Armed Services Editions weren't read in isolation — they were shared, torn apart, passed around, discussed in foxholes and on transports among men from every region and background the country could produce.

And here the exclusion problem returns with force. The mid-century civic infrastructure produced both education and empathy simultaneously — but within boundaries that excluded millions. The challenge of the present is not simply to rebuild what was lost. It is to build what has never existed: civic spaces that produce the education-empathy synthesis for a pluralistic, integrated society. The bowling leagues and union halls did extraordinary work within their walls. The question is whether we can build rooms that do the same work without the walls — without requiring homogeneity as the price of cohesion.

That is what we have lost. Not just education. Not just empathy. The spaces where both happened together. The institutions that produced civic virtue didn't do it by teaching people to be virtuous. They did it by creating conditions where knowledge and encounter were inseparable — where you couldn't learn without being in proximity to someone different, and you couldn't be in proximity without learning something.

The question is whether anything like that can be deliberately rebuilt — and here the essay's own logic creates a problem it must be honest about.

We are trying to run a republic on cognitive architecture that requires physical presence, within an infrastructure designed to eliminate it.

The argument presented here operates in two registers that do not fully resolve. The first is materialist: civic virtue emerges from specific economic and institutional conditions — shared struggle, limited alternatives, necessity — and recedes when those conditions change. If that analysis is correct, then civic virtue is not something that can be willed into existence. It is produced by pressure, and it dissolves when the pressure lifts. The second register is normative: the conditions that produce both education and empathy can be understood, and understanding them creates at least the possibility of deliberate reconstruction. But every historical example of the education-empathy synthesis — the union hall, the charrette, the wartime reading program — emerged under crisis. None was built in comfort. And the contact hypothesis research, while it demonstrates that prejudice reduction through structured encounter is real and replicable, has not yet produced a model for generating the civic infrastructure that a republic requires at the scale a republic demands.

This is not a contradiction the essay can resolve, because it is not a contradiction that anyone has resolved. It is the central problem of democratic theory in an age of comfort and fragmentation: the conditions that produce the capacities self-governance requires may be the very conditions that self-governance, when successful, eliminates. Jefferson's republic needs educated, engaged citizens. But the stability and prosperity that a well-functioning republic produces appear to erode the very engagement it depends on. That is not a failure of character. It is a structural paradox.

The lesson of the mid-century Great Compression is not that our grandparents were better people. The lesson is that their world forced them into rooms together because survival demanded it. The lesson of Durham is not that love conquers hate, but that a shared, inescapable crisis forced an Exalted Cyclops and a Black civil rights activist to sit at the same table long enough that something beneath conscious thought recalibrated. Five hundred and fifteen studies confirm that the mechanism is real. The historical record confirms that education and empathy, when produced together in shared spaces, generate something that functions as civic virtue. The biology confirms that the boundaries of the ingroup are not fixed.

But none of this tells us how to build those conditions deliberately, at scale, without the crisis that has historically forced people through the door. And it does not tell us how to do it within an infrastructure — digital, commercial, architectural — that is optimized to sort us apart.

If we expect a nation to be ignorant of its neighbors and remain free, we expect what never was and never will be. Jefferson knew that about knowledge. The neuroscience suggests it is equally true of proximity. A republic requires both — citizens who understand the system and citizens who can see each other across the boundaries the system creates.

Whether that is achievable without the catalyst of shared struggle is the question this essay leaves open. It is, in the end, the question the republic itself leaves open — and has from the beginning.
